          <h3 id="guide-top">Introduction</h3>
          <p>
            Before starting to use the website it is useful to distinguish between members and people.
          </p>
          <p>
          <ul>
            <li>A <strong>member</strong> is anyone who has signed up to use the website and will be a living member of our family. 
            <li>A <strong>person</strong> is someone, living or dead, about whom information is stored in the <strong>knowledgebase</strong>. We refer to the collection of data about a single person as a <b>record</b>. 
          </ul>
          <p>Normally, there will be a person record for each member. Once deceased, a member will no longer have a membership, but their person record will remain in the knowledgebase.
          </p>
          <p>
            The website has two major components: the membership page and the knowledgebase page. The <strong>membership page</strong> deals with signing up and signing in activities as well as communication between members. The <strong>knowledgebase page</strong> deals with viewing and maintaining the knowledgebase. 
          </p>
          
          <h3>Interacting with the knowledgebase</h3>
          <p>
            The knowledgebase is a collection of person records in the form of a family tree with each individual connected to their parents and their children (where this information is known). As a member of the website you can amend the information contained in (almost) any person record and you can add new people to the knowledgebase. When you sign up to be a member you will be asked to create a person record containing information about yourself. However, it may be the case that a person record for you is already in the knowledgebase, added there by another member. In this case you will be asked to view your record and, if you wish, add to it or amend whatever is already there.
          </p>
          <p>
           When you interact with the knowledgebase, you will often want to view specific person records. This means asking the system to find the appropriate person record and to display it for you. There are two ways to access a specific person record: either by specifying a person's name and their date of birth or by inputting the person's reference number (if you happen to know it). 
          </p>
          <p>
            Accessing a person record by inputting a name is useful when searching for someone for whom you do not have precise or detailed information. The system will search the knowledgebase for people who match, either exactly or approximately, the information you have supplied. If your data identifies more than a single person, you will be shown a list of all matching people from which you can select one to view.
          </p>
          <p>
            Whenever a person record is displayed you will see their reference number at the top of the display. The reference number can be used to access the person on future occasions. To help you remember reference numbers, there is a facility - known as 'remembering' - for you to record reference numbers and names of people you want to remember. You can access your list of remembered people to help in retrieving their full person record.
          </p>
          <p>
            The data in a person record is divided into two categories: identification data and personal details. If the person is living (and quite likely to be a member) you can view their identification data and those parts of their personal details that they have chosen to make public.  
          </p>
          <h3>Your personal data</h3>
          <p>
            As a member you have control over the majority of data in your person record. The intention is that identification data (name, date of birth, parents, children etc) relates to the structure of the family tree and is public, viewable by other members. Personal details are considered private unless you choose to make them public. As a member, you can add personal details to your record and choose which details to make public.
          </p>
          <p>
            A few years after your death, all your private data will become public. The idea is to make private data public only when it is safe to do so. That is, when it will not cause offense or embarassment to other members. Therefore, you can state when your private data becomes public but this cannot be indefinitely (otherwise, why record it in the first place?). Advice is currently being sought as to the full rules that should apply in this area.
          </p>
          <h3>Other persons' data</h3>
          <p>
            Any person record that relates to a deceased family member is viewable and editable by any member. This is the mechanism by which we build up the family tree: members add new people to the knowledgebase and add to the knowledge about people in the knowledgebase.
          </p>
          <p>
            All data contained in a person record relating to a living person but who is not currently a member is deemed public and can be viewed and edited by any other member. 
          </p>
          <p>
            When someone becomes a member they take control over their personal record (if one exists) and can choose to delete, amend or make private the data contained in it. At this point, other members cannot add or amend the data in that member's person record (though they can view the public data).
          </p>
          <h3>Children</h3>
          <p> 
            For privacy and security reasons, we distinguish between adults and children and we have chosen to define a child is anyone under the age of 16. Our current rules say that, normally, a child cannot be a member but there can be a person record for a child. A child's person record is controlled by its parents/guardians who decide which information to make public. A parent or guardian can choose to allow their child to become a member.
          </p>
          <p>
            The rules governing a child's use of the website are still being developed. It may be the case, for example, that a child should be able to view (some) data held in the knowledgebase but not allowed to amend data.
          </p>
          <h3>Developing the rules for using the website</h3>
          <p>
            The rules for accessing the website are a matter for agreement between members. 
          </p>
          <p>
            The website supports a mechanism for debate and agreement over the rules and administation of the website. Any member can suggest a topic for debate through the Notices and Opinionaire mechanisms. Any member can add a notice (notices appear on the right hand side of the Knowledgebase and Membership pages) and can suggest topics for discussion. Responses are added as notices. In due course, a fully fledged blog will be added to the website to support discussion.
          </p>
          <p>
            When a member wishes to canvass the opinion of other members more widely, they can create an opinionaire. The opinionaire mechanism allows a member to specify a statement that they would like other members to respond to (to vote on whether they agree or disagree with the statement). For example, there could be a statement expressing a wish to change a rule about the use of the website which, if enough members agree with the proposal, should be enacted (see The Role of Administrators). When creating an opinionaire the member can specify a date by which other members should respond (vote) and after which the result of the ballot will notified to all members.
          </p>
          <h3>The Role of Administrators</h3>
          <p>
            An administrator is a member who has volunteered to act as an administrator. The role of an administrator is to ensure the integrity of the website by, for example, answering queries about the website, removing offensive material, resolving disputes, reacting to members suggestions and maintaining the health of the website and its data. It is hoped that these duties will be minimal.
          </p>
          <p>
            The website has been designed to be, as far as possible, self governing but there has to be a mechanism for discussion and taking decisions based on those discussions. Administrators (there should be several) are responsible for carrying out the wishes of the general membership. Administrators' actions should be entirely reactive to the wishes of the membership.
          </p>
          <p>
            There should be several administrators at any point in time so that the work can be divided between them to make the role as lightweight as possible and to allow for discussion before taking action. A member can send an email to the administrators in confidence asking for action. 
          </p>
          <p>
            For example, it may be the case that members wish for a change in the rules governing the use of the website. Following an opionionaire, the administrators should discuss the outcome and arrange for the appropriate rule change. This may involve changes to the design of the website for which specialist help is required; how this is achieved and paid for is a matter for further discussion!
          </p>
